'''''Calostoma fuhreri''''' is a species of [[gasteroid fungi|gasteroid fungus]] in the family [[Sclerodermataceae]]. Found in Australia, the original specimens were collected by mycologist [[Bruce Fuhrer]], for whom the species is named. [[Basidiocarp|Fruit bodies]] grow to {{convert|28|mm|in|abbr=on}} tall, and comprise a [[stipe (mycology)|pseudostipe]] that is {{convert|15|–|20|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long by {{convert|5|–|8|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} thick that supports a roughly spherical [[peridium]] (spore sac). Atop the peridium is an irregular [[stoma]] (opening) that is red on the inside. Inside the peridium is a white [[gleba]] that consists of spores, [[basidium|basidia]], and broken [[hypha]]e. The spores are oblong to elliptical, [[hyaline]] (translucent), and typically measure 20–26 by 9–11&nbsp;[[micrometre|µm]].<ref name="Crichton 1986"/>

